The poet now states explicitly what he had previously expressed in allegorical language: his promise was afterwards fulfilled in the Aeneid, though (as C. observes) in amanner and method different from anything that is here suggested.

49, 50. For the chariot-races at Olympia see note on 1. 19. miratus =‘ coveting.’ Take ad aratra with sortes, and cp. ‘ fortis aratris,’ 1. 62.

For the following directions virgil is indebted to his predecessor Varro (Introd. p. 7). It should be observed that in ancient Italy cattle were bred prineipally for drauglzt purposes, not for meat: hence strength and size are the all-important qualities in the cow, since the calves take after their mothers.
